<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua Chronology,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Look At How The Nicaraguan Peace Process Evolved</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The negotiations to end Nicaragua's
six-year civil war between the leftist Sandinista government and
the U.S.-backed Contra rebels stem from the regional peace plan
signed by the presidents of five Central American nations.
   Here is a chronology detailing Nicaragua's participation in the
peace-seeking process:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   AUG. 7 _ Presidents of Costa Rica, Honduras, El Salvador,
Guatemala and Nicaragua sign peace plan sponsored by Costa Rican
President Oscar Arias. It includes amnesties for political
prisoners, democratic reforms, an end to foreign aid for rebel
armies, and a prohibition against one country's allowing guerrillas
to use its territory to attack another.
   NOV. 6 _ President Daniel Ortega asks Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo, archbishop of Managua, to mediate indirect cease-fire talks
between Sandinistas and Contras.
   NOV. 19-23 _ Nicaragua's National Assembly approves bills to
lift state of emergency and grant amnesty to some prisoners when
U.S. aid to Contras ends and other nations comply with regional
peace plan. Government frees 985 political prisoners in show of
compliance with plan.
   DEC. 3 _ Indirect talks between Sandinista government and
Contras begin in Dominican Republic, mediated by Obando y Bravo. No
progress in first round.
   DEC. 22 _ Second round of talks breaks off after Contras insist
on meeting face to face with Sandinistas. Both sides participate in
a two-day Christmas cease-fire, but there are many reports of
violence.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 16 _ Responding to pressure from other Central American
nations at meeting in Costa Rica, Ortega agrees to open direct
talks with Contras mediated by Obando y Bravo.
   JAN. 19 _ Nicaragua lifts six-year-old state of emergency in
Nicaragua.
   JAN. 28 _ First direct talks between Sandinistas and Contras
begin in Costa Rica.
   FEB. 18 _ Second round of talks lasts only one day and is broken
off by Obando y Bravo, who cites inflexibility on both sides.
Cardinal calls for talks to include democratic reforms.
   MAR. 2 _ After series of letters between Obando y Bravo and
Ortega, Ortega calls for face-to-face talks.
   MAR. 8 _ Contras back out of talks set for next day, citing lack
of preparation.
   MAR. 17 _ American troops arrive in Honduras as show of force
against Nicaragua, whose forces reportedly have crossed the
Honduran border in offensive against Contra rebels.
   MAR. 21 _ Contras and Sandinistas meet face-to-face for first
time in Nicaraguan territory at southern border post Sapoa. Each
announces halt to offensive military operations.
   MAR. 23 _ Sandinista leaders and Contra representatives announce
cease-fire plan that would end war by May 31.
   MAR. 27 _ Sandinistas free 100 political prisoners.
   MAR. 28 _ Technical teams meet at Sapoa again to discuss
mechanics of cease-fire.
   APR. 1 _ Formal truce begans.
   APR. 4 _ Second round of unsuccessful technical talks at Sapoa.
   APR. 14 _ Third round of technical talks begins.
   APR. 15 _ Contra leaders come to Managua for first time to hold
three days of high-level talks with Sandinistas.
   APR. 28 _ Second round of talks in Managua.
   MAY 26 _ Three days of meetings in Managua. Sandinistas offer
proposal following Contra demand for democratic reforms.
   MAY 31 _ Truce ends. Sandinistas extend it to June 30, Contras
agree to prolong cease-fire until June 9.
   JUNE 7 _ Two sides attempt talks for fourth time. Contras say
they will not resume meetings if no agreement is reached.
Sandinistas offer compromise plan calling for democratic reforms
before full disarmament by Oct. 10.
   JUNE 9 _ Contras reject Nicaraguan compromise plan. No new talks
scheduled.
</TEXT>
